		<credit project="CfPBoK@https://slebok.github.io/cfpbok/"/>
		<div class="right"><a href="index.html"><img src="../sle.png" alt="SLE 2013"></a><br><code>sle2013/paper08</code></div>
			<h1><span class="less"><a href="index.html">SLE 2013</a> paper:</span><br><i>Detecting Ambiguity in Programming Language Grammars</i></h1>
			<h2><a href="../profile/NaveneethaVasudevan.html">Naveneetha Vasudevan</a>, <a href="../profile/LaurenceTratt.html">Laurence Tratt</a></h2>
<ul><li>DOI: <a href="https://doi.org/10.1007/978-3-319-02654-1_9">10.1007/978-3-319-02654-1_9</a></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t5b.html"><span class="tagM">T5B: Language Description Analysis</span></a><ul><li> The main contribution is an analysis technique for detecting ambiguity in context-free grammars for programming languages.
</li></ul></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t5e.html"><span class="tagL">T5E: Empirical Evaluation</span></a><ul><li> The paper emphasizes evaluation via generated/random grammars (Boltzmann sampling, mutation) to test ambiguity-detection techniques at scale.
</li></ul></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t3a.html"><span class="tagL">T3A: Meta-languages</span></a><ul><li> Grammars are the analyzed artifacts, and the techniques operate at the level of grammar specifications.
</li></ul></li></ul>
